<br>
&quot;I do believe that you are not in any position to tell myself or anyone else how appropriate or inappropriate Vision's handling of Vision's affairs is, especially when all who were actually involved have no issues.<br>
<br>
Perhaps you should follow your own advise and not tell guilds that you hold no membership in and do not raid with as a guest as to how they should handle their loot.&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
First of all I never said a thing about vision's loot or loot system. It works for you guys, /cong .  Look back at that thread and you should notice my single post about loot systems was completely seperate from my conversation about the other.<br>
<br>
If I had brought up my name, in a post, for discussion about names, anyone could give me a longwinded version of how much it isn't right. After all, I brought my business to everyone's attention. As it stands the only time i mentioned my name was because someone asked who I was. The conversation was not about my name, and I didn't type my name to discuss the right or wrong of it, or give an example of a name. My name was there as a means of identification and nothing else.The majority of posters here put their name in their posts, however 99% of the time their names are not the topics of the posts.<br>
<br>
Vision's affair in that post was put up as an example for the public, as such it seems strange to complain about someone discussing the example your guild brought up.<br>
<br>
Do you see the difference?<br>
<br>
Pali, gonna break your post up to go with the individual points.<br>
<br>
&quot;If I go to PoG and spend hours of my own time, without the guild, perhaps when the guild is sleeping, to get a Robe of the Bonecaster - or if I hoard platinimum for a year and buy a Mana Robe, at what point would I be eligible for a Thurgadin, Skyshrine, Kael, or god-dropped robe?&quot;<br>
<br>
I'm gonna go out on a limb here and assume bonecaster is as good as thurg/ss. I am not up to date on necro items.<br>
<br>
The answer is you'd be about the last to be eligible for thurg, ss, kael robe. The reason being it is in the guild's interest to get everyone equipped well, correct?<br>
<br>
It would go against that goal to have 1 person who already has a comparable robe win a robe that could have gone to someone with a much worse item. Most people realize this, and when a roll like that would come up would say, &quot;Pass&quot;. I know the people I raid with would.<br>
<br>
&quot;If I have a 40% haste item, I'm ineligable for a 41% haste item. At what percentage do I become eligible? What if I recently traded my 40% haste item away to buy a luclin horse? Am I eligible now?&quot;<br>
<br>
If you already have a good haste item, say a CoF, and a %40 haste item drops you could roll. However if that  cof was guild gotten, it gets passed down upon your winning. If it wasn't guild gotten, I would be disappointed in said person if they didn't hand it down to be rolled for by everyone or given to the runner up on the 1st item(however that would be their choice). Much like in your system, a tank you load up with gear could take off when his set is completed and he has his epic. You trust your guildmates not to. I trust my guildmates to pass things down if they win better on a guild raid. I rolled on berserker gauntlets in PoG. If I had won I would have given my cobalt gauntlets to the other person rolling. This system relies on trust as much as yours does.<br>
<br>
&quot;You've reached the 8th (7th, count how you will) island in the Plane of Sky. Only one magician in your guild is still on the raid (all of the necromancers having accidentally fallen off of Bzzazzt isle). What do you do when the second magician epic crown drops? The going rate for this item is roughly 50k. This item is worth 50kpp to any member of your guild, not just magicians.&quot;<br>
<br>
Epic quest items are different. They are not loot in the traditional sense. The first and only mage on the raid would get his, and the second would go to the guild bank for whoever the first mage is to get to the point they need it. In the case of having say 3 mages at the raid with just one dropping, the mage closest to the point they need it would get the crown. 2 or more of them at that point? They roll or decide it among themselves. Yes, deciding it among the other members of your class there happens, but it isn't required.<br>
<br>
&quot;If I have three characters in your guild, a 60 Necromancer, a 54 Shadowknight, and a 54 Cleric, is it ok if I bring my Cleric to Hate and my Necromancer to Fear? If it is, what penalty is there to bringing my characters to events that benefit them?&quot;<br>
<br>
Sure, you could do that. Which character is your main? Alts get a chance at an item only if someone's main will not use it. A hate raid i was on not too long ago fits into this. I was the only warrior present who did not have indi arms when they dropped, aside from someone's alt who was also parked there. In this case I had &quot;dibs&quot; on them. If your necro was your main, and your cleric was an alt, your cleric would get a chance only at what the people who play their clerics as main characters do not need. <br>
<br>
Unless they pass it down to you. It happens. For example, I passed on the arms, because I was shopping for cobalt at the time, and would not use this item overlong- and being nodrop, i couldn't pass it down.<br>
<br>
&quot;You have raided Fear 100 times. You have killed Dread, Fright, and Terror (together) (and previously Dracoliche) 300 times. As a necro, you have always dreamed of a Staff of Undead Legions (look, just pretend, ok? I have one, it's fun.). On the 101st killing, a Staff of Undead Legions drops and you, a level 60 Necro who has raided Fear 100 times, and a fresh-off-probation level 46 Necro on his first trip to fear ever are there. Who gets to random for this item, as the level 46 Necro clearly has worse equipment?&quot;<br>
<br>
You both get a chance to random on the item. On the other hand yourself and the level 46 could decide it amongst yourselves &quot;Listen, I really want x item if it drops. In exchange you get x other item if it drops, as i don't want/need it as much, how does that sound?&quot;. Or maybe the level 46 would simply step aside? As far as the people I am and have raided with(in the past 6 months or so), that level 46 would most likely decide it with you, or roll, win, then say &quot;Nah man, you take it.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You've reached Overking Bathsoap in Chardok, and killed him. He has the cleric epic piece. You have 4 clerics there, and two of them have started their epic; but in doing so, they've missed guild-raids. Who do you let /random for the epic piece?&quot;<br>
<br>
That depends, is one of those clerics at the point where they are ready for this step? If they aren't..bank it till the first among them is at that step or give it to the closest to needing it. If more than one are, roll or decide amongst themselves. If someone planned the raid just for that piece and is at that step, they get it. If the others want it in the final case, they can plan a raid themselves, and I'm sure the first would help them do so.<br>
<br>
&quot;What happens to the award system when your top 5 tanks all go to raids and all are good tanks? Who gets first call on a drop? Allamar does. The simplicity of our system... <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> &quot;<br>
<br>
This is what /random does different. If you have 5 people who all help out, have been with the guild around the same time, and all are around the same level, it doesn't seem fair at all to repeatedly give the same person first dibs loot. If that person were me, I'd feel rather guilty for getting the results of everyone's labors so often. However if several different pieces drop for these tanks, almost a complete set, and everyone /randoms it, everyone has the same shot at what they all worked for. Win a piece, out of rolls till everyone has looted one. Instead of having one really well equipped tank, you now have 5 decently equipped tanks, and they all know they got a fair shake in the deal.<br>
<br>
&quot;The moral of the story is good things come to those who wait.&quot;<br>
<br>
Indeed. The more raids you attend and help out on the better your chances at having gear. Your system awards for work put in after it has been done. This system awards for work people do as they are doing it.<br>
<br>
The person who is never at raids but comes to that 1 raid and wins something is ultimately the loser- as the guy who went to several and was missing only that piece has virtually the complete set. This is rewarding for the things you do without having to have a person in charge of seeing you get whats coming to you. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/upalimaxsceleris.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Palimax Sceleris</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Local Resident</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/17/02 1:19:14 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=818.topic&index=60>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Dear Menn..er Logix</span><hr size=1> In nearly every one of the tough situations you suggested, you gave interesting answers, and in very few of them was /random the method used to determine the outcome.<br>
<br>
